## Q1. Why does HashMap always keep its capacity as a power of 2?

### Answer

HashMap keeps its capacity as a power of 2 (16, 32, 64, 128...) because it calculates the bucket index using:

```java
bucket = hash & (capacity - 1);
```

When the capacity is a power of 2, `(capacity - 1)` becomes a bitmask containing all 1s.

Examples:

| Capacity | Capacity - 1 | Binary Mask |
|----------|--------------|-------------|
|16|15|1111|
|32|31|11111|
|64|63|111111|
|128|127|1111111|

This allows the bitwise AND operation to preserve all the lower bits of the hash while efficiently calculating the bucket index.

If the capacity were not a power of 2 (for example, 10), then:

```
10 - 1 = 9
```

Binary:

```
1001
```

The mask contains 0s between 1s, causing some hash bits to be discarded. This leads to more collisions because different hash values may map to the same bucket.

### Interview Takeaway

Power-of-two capacity ensures:

- Efficient bucket calculation.
- Better bucket distribution.
- Fewer collisions.
- Faster lookup performance.

