## Q3. Why does HashMap use `h ^ (h >>> 16)`?

### Answer

HashMap performs hash spreading before calculating the bucket index.

```java
hash = h ^ (h >>> 16);
```

The goal is to mix the higher 16 bits of the hash code into the lower 16 bits.

This is necessary because the bucket index uses only the lower bits.

Without hash spreading:

```
Hash A

xxxxxxxx0001

Hash B

yyyyyyyy0001
```

Although the higher bits are different, both hashes have the same lower bits and would map to the same bucket.

After applying:

```java
h ^ (h >>> 16)
```

information from the higher bits is mixed into the lower bits.

As a result, keys are distributed more uniformly across buckets, reducing collisions.

### Interview Takeaway

Hash spreading improves bucket distribution by ensuring that both higher and lower bits influence the final bucket index.

