## Q4. Why does HashMap use the unsigned right shift operator (`>>>`) instead of the signed right shift operator (`>>`)?

### Answer

Java provides two right shift operators.

```java
>>
```

Signed Right Shift

```java
>>>
```

Unsigned Right Shift

The signed right shift (`>>`) copies the sign bit into the new positions.

For negative hash codes, this fills the leftmost bits with 1s.

Example:

```
11110000111100001111000011110000
```

After signed right shift:

```
11111111111111111111000011110000
```

This introduces extra 1s from the sign bit and reduces the effectiveness of hash spreading.

The unsigned right shift (`>>>`) always fills the new leftmost bits with 0s.

Example:

```
11110000111100001111000011110000
```

After unsigned right shift:

```
00000000000000001111000011110000
```

This preserves the original bit pattern without introducing sign extension.

As a result, XOR produces a better-distributed hash.

### Interview Takeaway

HashMap uses `>>>` because hash spreading should depend only on the original hash bits, not on whether the hash code is positive or negative.

